{"id":"1609.09262","submitter":"David Bowler","authors":"Keisuke Sagisaka, Jun Nara, David Bowler","title":"Importance of bulk states for the electronic structure of semiconductor\n  surfaces: implications for finite slabs","comments":"14 pages; submitted to J. Phys.:Condens. Matter; revised in response\n  to referees' comments","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1361-648X/aa5f91","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate the influence of slab thickness on the electronic structure of\nthe Si(100)-p(2x2) surface in density functional theory (DFT) calculations,\nconsidering both density of states and band structure. Our calculations, with\nslab thicknesses of up to 78 atomic layers, reveal that the slab thickness\nprofoundly affects the surface band structure, particularly the dangling bond\nstates of the silicon dimers near the Fermi level. We find that, to precisely\nreproduce the surface bands, the slab thickness needs to be large enough to\ncompletely converge the bulk bands in the slab. In case of the Si(100) surface,\nthe dispersion features of the surface bands, such as the band shape and width,\nconverge when the slab thickness is larger than 30 layers. Complete convergence\nof both the surface and bulk bands in the slab is only achieved when the slab\nthickness is greater than 60 layers.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 29 Sep 2016 09:03:27 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 22 Nov 2016 14:14:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-04-05"}
